8/ In the future people will be earning more and more of their income from these digital games/metaverses.  That onboarding starts now.Disclosure: I am invested in @MeritCircle_IO @ReadyPlayerDAO @BlackpoolHQ  and advising @HoogaGaming

7/ The "competition" in the DAO/guild space is actually good for the ecosystem.  It will ensure that abusive and exploitative tactics are less likely to occur.They will also be very symbiotic with the games themselves as each will rely on the other for growth and longevity.

6/ It is for this reason that I'm super excited to be watching what groups like @YieldGuild @MeritCircle_IO @ReadyPlayerDAO @HoogaGaming @LootSquadGG and @BlackpoolHQ are going to bring their respective regions and communities onboard.

5/ For this reason there will be very focused and regionalized DAOs/guilds/organizations popping up all over the world that will do their part to onboard local communities onto P2E.  My belief is that there will be many organizations not just one that will do this.

4/ But in order for these games to scale and be successful it will require lots of local coordination.  Friends family and neighbors will be onboarding each other all over different parts of the globe.  This is a very LOCAL process.

3/ Thanks to the great success of @AxieInfinity much focus is now turning to P2E.  The impact of these games is not to be taken lightly.  Hundreds of thousands people's lives are already changing and that number will continue to grow over time.
2/ Everything that is being built today is laying the foundational groundwork for how humans will interact in the future.At our most fundamental level we are all still just like our tribal ancestors.

1/A huge part of the NFT thesis is personal connection.  Once you understand that behind all the tech and innovation we are all just humans interacting with each other things begin to make much more sense.

6/ The amount of publicity generated far outstripped the amount spent.  And every CMO at every corporation around the world should take note of this:  IT'S STILL AN ASSET ON THE BALANCE SHEET

13/ I should add: a big thank you to the many employees who stepped in to fill the gaps that were left as our colleagues departed working nights and weekends to ensure we continued to serve our customers. This was heroic and awesome to see.

12/ It's incredibly difficult to do but if you stand up and say what you really think it may turn out better than you thought. Saying this advice for myself as much as anyone else - there will be many more challenges ahead.
11/ For leaders out there think about any area where you aren't being 100% authentic and instead are trying to keep the peace or say what you think people want to hear.
10/ You will get lots of attacks online and not everyone will agree but ultimately people want clarity and authenticity from leaders not platitudes. It will come back to you tenfold.
9/ The biggest lesson I took away from the whole ordeal is that if you believe something is the right path it's worth speaking up about it even if it's controversial.

8/ The only sense I can make of it is that there is a huge mismatch between peoples stated and revealed preferences right now and we're operating in an environment of virtue signaling and fear of speaking up.

7/ In fact I would say it was probably the most positive reaction I've gotten from any change I've made in the history of the company which is saying something. How could something be so negative in the press but turn out to be incredibly positive with every stakeholder.

6/ While the media reports were mostly negative and it even spawned some retaliatory and intellectually dishonest hit pieces the reaction both from employees and people I spoke to in private was overwhelmingly positive.
5/ What was amazing was the contrast between the news following my post and the reaction from employees and people who spoke to me in private.

4/ Several people told me this would never happen when I circulated the original draft internally. It turns out that there are people from every background who want to work at a mission focused company.

3/ One of the biggest concerns around our stance was that it would impact our diversity numbers. Since my post we've grown our headcount about 110% while our diversity numbers have remained the same or even improved on some metrics.

2/ We have a much more aligned company now where we can focus on getting work done toward our mission. And it has allowed us to hire some of the best talent from organizations where employees are fed up with politics infighting and distraction.

Today I was honored to add this historic work to the Medici CollectionI encourage you to enjoy not only this work but to visit https://t.co/7X4Lte20nN & learn more about the magic of @VanArmanTo Pinder and the innovators who pave the way for all of us I raise my glassüç∑

After seeing how some artists show little regard for their collectors and instead chase the next dollar I was moved by Pinder's candor and integrity.He went on to share that @Pr0mETHe_us was considering listing his AI Imagined Face. Thankfully he did so.

"... If I minted unlimited amounts it would dilute the value of the 5 current holders. @XCOPYART matrix @Pr0mETHe_us @ArtonymousArt and @Hackatao. I am sure you can respect me protecting their early investment in my art and rewarding it."
"I do not revisit old projects so would be unable to do a pure AI Imagined face. I believe in protecting the scarcity of my previous work and that project is over...
Despite my interest acquiring one of these works felt out of reach. Only 5 exist. All from 2018. I asked Pinder if he would ever mint another.His response spoke volumes:

It was a haunting thought to imagine an artificially intelligent being casually painting across the canvas a human skull...Here is "Neural Net Imagined Portrait #3" owned by @XCOPYART. I can see why it is one of his favorites... https://t.co/9EwsQnJBGo

But to be honest I still did not feel complete. For what had struck me the most were Pinder's early works the AI Imagined Faces.In these works the AI imagines what a human face looks like and creates what it sees.

Luckily an auction for 3 of his infamous "BitGANs" was on the horizon. I bid strongly for Cyber Zombie 10366 which Pinder had said was his favorite of the 3... and let us face it:I am addicted to zombies :)I was victorious and happy to own this new fren https://t.co/qn6UuTUa3T

When I first stumbled upon his work I found myself mesmerized. I had never heard of robots painting much less like this.Seeing works in hands of some of our greatest collectors such as @krybharat @Anonymoux2311 and @2Yeahyeah let me know I was not alone in my appreciation
This portrait of @Coldie shows what his robots can do now: https://t.co/ReoDsVarPu

"... My most recent robots however use deep learning neural networks artificial intelligence feedback loops and computational creativity to make a surprising amount of independent aesthetic decisions. "

Pinder Van Arman has spent the last 15 years teaching machines how to paint. In his words:"When I began with my first machines fifteen years ago they were only capable of simple tasks like connecting dots and painting by numbers..."

Once in a great while the sky parts & an opportunity appears to acquire a historic relic from the early days of NFTPresenting "AI Imagined Portrait #2" by @VanArmanSuperRare token #115 & 1st place winner in the 2018 Robot Art ContestHere is the story of it's acquisitionüëá https://t.co/bmWg3uHyZz
